tion 3: Use the square root of the remaining space.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    return np.sqrt(remaining) * (remaining >= 0)\n\nFunction 4: Use the reciprocal of the remaining space plus 1.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    return 1 / (remaining + 1e-9) * (remaining >= 0)\n\nFunction 5: Combine remaining space with the bin size.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    return remaining * (bins / (item + 1))  # Higher bin size and smaller remaining is better\n\nFunction 6: Use the arcsin of the ratio.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio = item / bins\n    return np.arcsin(ratio) * (ratio <= 1)\n\nFunction 7: Use the square of the remaining space.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    return remaining ** 2 * (remaining >= 0)\n\nFunction 8: Use the logarithm of the bin size plus the item.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(bins + item) * (bins >= item)\n\nWait, but if bins are smaller than item, they can't fit. So perhaps the priority is zero for those. Alternatively, multiply by (bins >= item).\n\nFunction 9: Use the arctangent of the ratio.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio = item / bins\n    return np.arctan(ratio) * (ratio <= 1)\n\nFunction 10: Use the reciprocal of the bin size minus the item.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return 1 / (bins - item + 1e-9) * (bins >= item)\n\nWait, but this might not cover all cases. Maybe I should ensure that each function uses a unique combination of operations.\n\nAlternatively, I can think of using different functions in combination, like adding a sine or cosine term.\n\nLet me try to make each function unique in terms of the mathematical operations used.\n\nFunction 3: Maybe use the square root of the remaining space multiplied by the item.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    return np.sqrt(remaining) * item * (remaining >= 0)\n\nFunction 4: Use the logarithm of the remaining space plus 1.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    return np.log(remaining + 1) * (remaining >= 0)\n\nFunction 5: Use the exponential of the ratio of item to bin size.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio = item / bins\n    return np.exp(ratio) * (ratio <= 1)\n\nFunction 6: Use the arcsin of the remaining space.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    return np.arcsin(remaining) * (remaining >= 0)\n\nWait, but arcsin requires the argument to be between -1 and 1. So if remaining is larger than 1, it's invalid. So perhaps I should clamp the remaining to a certain range.\n\nAlternatively, use arcsin of (remaining / bins) to keep it within [-1, 1].\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio = (bins - item) / bins\n    return np.arcsin(ratio) * (bins >= item)\n\nFunction 7: Use the square of the ratio of item to bin size.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio = item / bins\n    return ratio ** 2 * (ratio <= 1)\n\nFunction 8: Use the cube of the remaining space.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    return remaining ** 3 * (remaining >= 0)\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1) + np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.sqrt(item)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndar