ion 8 could combine log, exp, and sin: (np.log(bins + 1) * np.exp(item)) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins).\n- Function 9 could use cos and sqrt: np.cos(np.pi * item / np.sqrt(bins)).\n- Function 10 might involve a more complex combination, like (np.log(bins + 1) + np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item) + np.sin(item / bins).\n\nWait, but I need to make sure each function is unique in the way it combines operations. Maybe I should vary the functions more, using different trigonometric functions and different array operations each time.\n\nAlternatively, I can vary the order of operations, like adding, subtracting, multiplying, or dividing different combinations of the item and bins.\n\nLet me list out each function with a unique combination:\n\n1. Use log and add the item.\n2. Use log and multiply by mean.\n3. Use sin and cos in a sum.\n4. Use sqrt and exp in a product.\n5. Use log and exp in a product, then add mean.\n6. Use tan and subtract mean.\n7. Use arcsin and multiply by pi.\n8. Use log, exp, and sin in a sum.\n9. Use cos and sqrt in a product.\n10. Use log, exp, and sin in a more complex way.\n\nWait, but I need to make sure each function is unique. So, perhaps each function should have a distinct combination of operations. For example, some functions can use log and exp, others can use sin and cos, others can use sqrt and tan, etc.\n\nLet me think of each function step by step.\n\nFunction 1: item multiplied by log(bins + 1) plus min(bins).\nFunction 2: (log(bins +1) * mean(bins)) multiplied by item.\nFunction 3: sin(pi * item / bins) + cos(pi * item / bins).\nFunction 4: sqrt(bins) multiplied by exp(item).\nFunction 5: (log(bins +1) + exp(item)) multiplied by mean(bins).\nFunction 6: tan(item - mean(bins)).\nFunction 7: arcsin(item / bins) multiplied by pi.\nFunction 8: (log(bins +1) * exp(item)) + sin(pi * item / bins).\nFunction 9: cos(pi * item / sqrt(bins)).\nFunction 10: (log(bins +1) + mean(bins)) * exp(item) + sin(item / bins).\n\nWait, but function 3 uses sin 